<h1 style="color: #5e9ca0;">Diet</h1>
<h2 style="color: #2e6c80;">The platypus is a&nbsp;<a title="Carnivore" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carnivore">carnivore</a>: it feeds on&nbsp;<a title="Annelid" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annelid">annelid</a>&nbsp;worms,&nbsp;<a title="Larva" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larva">insect larvae</a>, freshwater&nbsp;<a title="Shrimp" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shrimp">shrimp</a>, and&nbsp;<a title="Cherax" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cherax">freshwater yabby</a>&nbsp;that it digs out of the riverbed with its snout or catches while swimming. It uses cheek-pouches to carry prey to the surface, where it is eaten.<sup id="cite_ref-parks_52-2" class="reference"></sup>&nbsp;The platypus needs to eat about 20% of its own weight each day, which requires it to spend an average of 12 hours daily looking for food.<sup id="cite_ref-Bethge_54-1" class="reference"></sup></h2>
